      "title": "The Compromises That Became the Curriculum",
      "hook": "Judges 1 records Israel's military successes in detail — and then, tribe by tribe, lists every city they failed to conquer, because the partial obedience of Judges 1 becomes the complete catastrophe of Judges 2-21.",
      "teaching": "Judges opens immediately after Joshua's death with the same question that opens every crisis in the Historical Books: 'Who of us is to go up first against the Canaanites?' Israel inquires of the Lord, receives a specific answer — Judah — and the campaign begins. The opening victories are real and significant. Judah and Simeon together capture Jerusalem, defeat the king of the Negev, and take Hebron, Debir, and Gaza. God is delivering the enemies into Israel's hands. The conquest is working.\n\nBut Judges 1 contains a refrain that begins to appear with increasing frequency and increasing weight: 'they did not drive them out.' Verse 19: Judah could not drive out the people of the plain because they had iron chariots. Verse 21: the Benjaminites did not drive out the Jebusites. Verses 27-33: Manasseh, Ephraim, Zebulun, Asher, and Naphtali all failed to drive out the Canaanites. Verse 34: the Amorites confined the Danites to the hill country. The list of failures accumulates like a legal indictment — tribe by tribe, city by city, until the pattern is unmistakable.\n\nThe most theologically revealing detail in Judges 1 is the reason given for each failure. It is never military inability. The Canaanites had iron chariots — but that is not a sufficient reason for a people whose God had parted the Jordan and thrown hailstones at the coalition armies. The failure is not technological; it is covenantal. Israel did not drive out the Canaanites because they chose not to — because it was easier to impose tribute and use their labour than to execute the covenant command. Compromise was more convenient than obedience.\n\nThe Angel of the Lord at Bokim in Judges 2:1-5 is the theological verdict on Judges 1. He comes up from Gilgal — where the covenant had been renewed after the Jordan crossing — and delivers a judicial speech: 'I brought you up out of Egypt and led you into the land I swore to give your ancestors. I said, 'I will never break my covenant with you, and you shall not make a covenant with the people of this land, but you shall break down their altars.' Yet you have disobeyed me. Why have you done this?' The people wept. They named the place Bokim — 'weeping.' But weeping is not repentance. The text does not say they obeyed afterward.\n\nJudges 2:10-23 introduces the theological framework that will govern the entire book: a cycle of sin, oppression, crying out, deliverance, and renewed sin. 'After that whole generation had been gathered to their ancestors, another generation grew up who knew neither the Lord nor what he had done for Israel.' The problem is not the Canaanite enemies; the problem is generational amnesia. The covenant's preservation requires transmission, and when transmission fails, the covenant unravels in a single generation. The judges are God's merciful interruptions of a cycle that, left to itself, would have destroyed Israel entirely.",
